ask: cdx dpa_ipsec xfrm_state ref leak + sa_id_name overflow (audit B5)

AUDIT-cdx.md P0.06, P0.08 — re-verifies prior audit C5, C7.

P0.06 — xfrm_state_lookup_byhandle ref leak in IPsec exception path.
ipsec_dqrr() in cdx/dpa_ipsec.c calls xfrm_state_lookup_byhandle()
which takes a refcount on the xfrm_state. Ownership is transferred to
the skb at "sp->xvec[0] = x" (after skb_ext_add); on every drop path
between the successful lookup and that assignment the ref leaks. Two
such paths exist:

  1. dpaa_eth_refill_bpools() failure -> goto pkt_drop (x leaked)
  2. skb_ext_add() -> NULL -> goto pkt_drop (x leaked)

Both originally jumped to a label that only does dev_kfree_skb() and
dpa_fd_release(), with no xfrm_state_put().

Fix: introduce a new label pkt_drop_xfrm: which calls xfrm_state_put(x)
and falls through to pkt_drop:. Both early-drop sites now goto
pkt_drop_xfrm. Note pkt_drop: itself is gated by
CONFIG_INET_IPSEC_OFFLOAD || CONFIG_INET6_IPSEC_OFFLOAD -- the new
label sits OUTSIDE that #if so it is always emitted, since the gotos
are unconditional. This removes the gate's purpose for pkt_drop:
itself, but keeps source-level minimal disturbance; pkt_drop: remains
referenced only from the now-redirected sites under the same #if (none
remain in the wild, the gate is harmless).

P0.08 — sa_id_name[8] stack overflow.
init_ipsec_sa() declares "uint8_t sa_id_name[8] = """ then does
sprintf(sa_id_name, "0x%x", handle). For handle > 0xFFFF the formatted
string is "0x" + 5..8 hex digits + NUL = 8..11 bytes, overflowing the
8-byte buffer onto the stack. This is reachable via every SA install.

Fix: widen buffer to [12] (covers full u32 handle + "0x" + NUL) and
switch to snprintf with sizeof(sa_id_name).

No behaviour change on success paths.

